Note: ============================================================================
Note: ERLANG PRINTER - Frontend AST Source Generator
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Formats the frontend parser's ErlangModule AST back to readable Erlang
Note: source code. Operates on frontend AST types (not HIR), so it is co-located
Note: with the frontend (sister to erlang_parser.runa / erlang_to_hir.runa).
Note: The independent HIR -> Erlang pipeline lives in
Note: backends/erlang/hir_to_erlang.runa.
Note: Handles: indentation, line breaking, Erlang syntax conventions
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_parser.runa" as ErlangParser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as DictPrim

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EMITTER CONFIGURATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emitter formatting context that threads through every emission routine.
indent_size sets the per-level width (Erlang convention is 4 spaces),
indent_level tracks current depth so increase/decrease are O(1) integer
ops rather than string-stack manipulations. current_column and
max_line_length together enable line-break decisions when output would
exceed the soft margin.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four Integer fields stored as a Runa struct. The pointer to this struct
is threaded through every emit_* function as the `config` parameter so
state is shared without globals. indent_size=4 is the Erlang community
standard; max_line_length=100 matches the OTP guideline.
@End Implementation

Type called "ErlangEmitterConfig":
    indent_size as Integer
    indent_level as Integer
    current_column as Integer
    max_line_length as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Factory for the default Erlang emitter configuration. Defaults match
OTP coding-style guidance so the emitter output reads as idiomatic
Erlang without per-call tuning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs an ErlangEmitterConfig with indent_size=4 (OTP standard),
indent_level=0 (top-level), current_column=0 (start of line), and
max_line_length=100 (OTP soft margin). Returns the struct pointer
for use as the config argument across the whole emitter.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_emitter_config" returns Integer:
    Let config be a value of type ErlangEmitterConfig
    Set config.indent_size to 4
    Set config.indent_level to 0
    Set config.current_column to 0
    Set config.max_line_length to 100
    Return config
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a fresh whitespace prefix matching the current indent depth.
Recomputing each call rather than caching is acceptable because
indent strings are short and indent levels rarely exceed single
digits in real Erlang code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Multiplies indent_level by indent_size to get total_spaces, then
loops 1..total_spaces appending a single space each iteration.
Returns the assembled string. No cap on indent depth — pathological
deeply-nested AST will produce wide indents but no truncation.
@End Implementation

Process called "indent" that takes config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let spaces be ""
    Let total_spaces be config.indent_level multiplied by config.indent_size

    For i from 1 to total_spaces:
        Set spaces to spaces joined with " "
    End For

    Return spaces
End Process

@Reasoning:
In-place mutation of the indent cursor when entering a nested
construct (case body, function body, list comprehension body).
Side-effecting on the config object lets every subsequent indent
call see the new depth without explicit threading.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single increment of indent_level. No range check — the matching
decrease_indent on exit is the only thing that can return it.
@End Implementation

Process called "increase_indent" that takes config as Integer returns Nothing:
    Set config.indent_level to config.indent_level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counterpart to increase_indent. Guards against going below zero
because emit routines occasionally call exit-paths multiple times
on error and double-decrement should not produce negative indent
(which would underflow when multiplied by indent_size).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If indent_level > 0 decrements; otherwise no-op. The guard makes
this idempotent at the zero boundary, simplifying error-path code.
@End Implementation

Process called "decrease_indent" that takes config as Integer returns Nothing:
    If config.indent_level is greater than 0:
        Set config.indent_level to config.indent_level minus 1
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE EMISSION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level emitter that produces a complete Erlang source file from an
ErlangModule AST. Emits the canonical module section order: attributes
(including the mandatory -module declaration), then records, then type
declarations, then function definitions. Blank lines between sections
and between functions match OTP style.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds the output incrementally with string concatenation through four
sequential sections. Attributes are followed by one blank line if any
were emitted. Records and types each get two trailing newlines for the
blank-line separator. Functions iterate with index so the last function
omits the trailing blank line — the file naturally ends after the last
function's terminating period.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_module" that takes module as ErlangModule, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be ""

    Note: Emit module attributes
    For Each attr in module.attributes:
        Set output to output joined with emit_attribute with attr, config
        Set output to output joined with "\n"
    End For

    Note: Add blank line after attributes
    Let module_attributes be module.attributes
    Let module_attr_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with module_attributes
    If module_attr_count is greater than 0:
        Set output to output joined with "\n"
    End If

    Note: Emit records
    For Each record in module.records:
        Set output to output joined with emit_record with record, config
        Set output to output joined with "\n"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"
    End For

    Note: Emit type declarations
    For Each type_decl in module.types:
        Set output to output joined with emit_type_decl with type_decl, config
        Set output to output joined with "\n"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"
    End For

    Note: Emit functions. Count computed once into a local; While loop because
    Note: stage1 codegen mis-evaluates a `For ... to <proc call> minus 1` bound.
    Let module_functions be module.functions
    Let module_functions_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with module_functions
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than module_functions_total:
        Let func be proc list_get from ListPrim with module_functions, i

        Set output to output joined with emit_function with func, config
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Note: Add blank line between functions
        If i is less than module_functions_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with "\n"
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return output
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ATTRIBUTE EMISSION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits Erlang module attributes which have the form -name(value).
or -name. for valueless attributes. Three attribute kinds need
specialised formatting: -module(Name) takes a bare atom, -export/-import
take a list of Name/Arity entries, and generic attributes take an
expression list. Routing through specialised paths produces idiomatic
output instead of Term-printer fallbacks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Always starts with `-` and the attribute type name. When attr_values
is non-empty: opens `(`, then dispatches on attr_type. "module"
inlines attr_values[0] as a bare atom. "export"/"import" emit
`[Name/Arity, ...]` from a list of {name, arity} dictionaries. Generic
fallback emits each value through emit_term separated by `, `. All
paths close with `)`. Finally appends `.` as required by Erlang
attribute syntax.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_attribute" that takes attr as ErlangAttribute, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be "-"
    Let attr_type be attr.attr_type
    Let attr_values be attr.attr_values
    Set output to output joined with attr_type

    Let attr_values_count be proc list_length from ListPrim with attr_values
    If attr_values_count is greater than 0:
        Set output to output joined with "("

        Note: Format attribute values based on type
        If attr_type is equal to "module":
            Let module_name be proc list_get from ListPrim with attr_values, 0
            Set output to output joined with module_name

        Otherwise If attr_type is equal to "export" or attr_type is equal to "import":
            Set output to output joined with "["

            Let export_list be proc list_get from ListPrim with attr_values, 0
            Let export_list_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with export_list
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than export_list_total:
                Let func_info be proc list_get from ListPrim with export_list, i
                Let func_info_name be proc get from DictPrim with func_info, "name"
                Set output to output joined with func_info_name
                Set output to output joined with "/"
                Let func_info_arity be proc get from DictPrim with func_info, "arity"
                Let arity_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with func_info_arity
                Set output to output joined with arity_str

                If i is less than export_list_total minus 1:
                    Set output to output joined with ", "
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            Set output to output joined with "]"

        Otherwise:
            Note: Generic attribute values
            Let generic_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with attr_values
            Let gi be 0
            While gi is less than generic_total:
                Let attr_value be proc list_get from ListPrim with attr_values, gi
                Let term_str be emit_term with attr_value
                Set output to output joined with term_str

                If gi is less than generic_total minus 1:
                    Set output to output joined with ", "
                End If
                Set gi to gi plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set output to output joined with ")"
    End If

    Set output to output joined with "."

    Return output
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RECORD EMISSION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Erlang record declaration syntax is -record(Name, {field, field = Default,
field :: Type, ...}). Field defaults use `=`, type annotations use `::`,
both are optional per field. Multi-field records get one field per line
for readability, matching OTP coding-style conventions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Opens with `-record(Name, {`. If fields list is non-empty: emits newline,
increases indent, then iterates fields. Each field emits at the
current indent followed by its name, optional ` = default` (only if
default_value is non-zero), optional ` :: type` (only if field_type is
non-zero), trailing `,` (only when not the last field), then newline.
After the loop decreases indent and re-emits the indent prefix so the
closing brace aligns with `-record`. Finishes with `})` followed by `.`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_record" that takes record as ErlangRecord, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be "-record("
    Set output to output joined with record.name
    Set output to output joined with ", {"

    Let record_fields be record.fields
    Let record_fields_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with record_fields
    If record_fields_total is greater than 0:
        Set output to output joined with "\n"
        Call increase_indent with config

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than record_fields_total:
            Let field be proc list_get from ListPrim with record_fields, i

            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with field.name

            Note: Emit default value. Field handle bound to a local before the
            Note: call (stage1 mis-evaluates an inline `obj.field` call argument).
            Let field_default be field.default_value
            If field_default is not equal to 0:
                Set output to output joined with " = "
                Set output to output joined with emit_expression with field_default, config
            End If

            Note: Emit type annotation
            Let field_type_expr be field.field_type
            If field_type_expr is not equal to 0:
                Set output to output joined with " :: "
                Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with field_type_expr, config
            End If

            If i is less than record_fields_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ","
            End If

            Set output to output joined with "\n"
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config
        Set output to output joined with indent with config
    End If

    Set output to output joined with "})."

    Return output
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE DECLARATION EMISSION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits -type, -opaque, or -spec declarations. The decl_type field selects
which (it stores the literal keyword). Type variables (the polymorphism
parameters in `-type list(T) :: ...`) are emitted in parentheses after
the name when present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Output begins with `-` followed by decl_type (e.g., "type"), a space,
and the declaration name. If type_vars is non-empty, emits them in
parentheses comma-separated. Then ` :: ` and the type expression
through emit_type_expr. Closes with `.` per Erlang attribute syntax.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_type_decl" that takes type_decl as ErlangTypeDecl, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be "-"
    Set output to output joined with type_decl.decl_type
    Set output to output joined with " "
    Set output to output joined with type_decl.name

    Note: Emit type variables
    Let type_decl_vars be type_decl.type_vars
    Let type_decl_vars_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with type_decl_vars
    If type_decl_vars_total is greater than 0:
        Set output to output joined with "("

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than type_decl_vars_total:
            Let type_var be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_decl_vars, i
            Set output to output joined with type_var

            If i is less than type_decl_vars_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set output to output joined with ")"
    End If

    Set output to output joined with " :: "
    Let type_decl_type_expr be type_decl.type_expr
    Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with type_decl_type_expr, config
    Set output to output joined with "."

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatches Erlang type expressions across seven shapes: atom, type
variable, parameterized application, list, tuple, fun (function type),
binary, and union. Each shape has its own syntactic surface in Erlang
(e.g., union uses `|`, fun uses `fun(...) -> ...`, tuple uses braces).
Recursive call handles nested types like list(tuple(integer, atom)).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on type_kind string. "atom"/"var" emit the first type_arg
directly. "parameterized" emits Name(arg1, arg2, ...) with recursive
emit_type_expr for each arg from index 1 onward. "list" wraps a single
inner type in `[...]`. "tuple" wraps comma-separated types in `{...}`.
"fun" emits `fun(arg1, ..., argN-1) -> argN` where the last type_arg
is the return type. "binary" emits the literal `<<>>` (binary type
syntax). "union" emits types separated by ` | `. Unknown kinds fall
through with an empty string.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_type_expr" that takes type_expr as ErlangTypeExpr, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be ""
    Let type_kind be type_expr.type_kind
    Let type_args be type_expr.type_args

    Let type_args_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with type_args

    If type_kind is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_type be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, 0
        Set output to atom_type

    Otherwise If type_kind is equal to "var":
        Let var_type be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, 0
        Set output to var_type

    Otherwise If type_kind is equal to "parameterized":
        Let param_name be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, 0
        Set output to param_name
        Set output to output joined with "("

        Let i be 1
        While i is less than type_args_total:
            Let arg be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, i
            Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with arg, config

            If i is less than type_args_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set output to output joined with ")"

    Otherwise If type_kind is equal to "list":
        Set output to "["

        If type_args_total is greater than 0:
            Let inner be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, 0
            Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with inner, config
        End If

        Set output to output joined with "]"

    Otherwise If type_kind is equal to "tuple":
        Set output to "{"

        Let ti be 0
        While ti is less than type_args_total:
            Let arg be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, ti
            Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with arg, config

            If ti is less than type_args_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ", "
            End If
            Set ti to ti plus 1
        End While

        Set output to output joined with "}"

    Otherwise If type_kind is equal to "fun":
        Set output to "fun("

        Note: Parameter types (all but last). Bound computed once into a local.
        Let fun_param_bound be type_args_total minus 1
        Let fi be 0
        While fi is less than fun_param_bound:
            Let arg be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, fi
            Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with arg, config

            If fi is less than fun_param_bound minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ", "
            End If
            Set fi to fi plus 1
        End While

        Set output to output joined with ") -> "

        Note: Return type (last arg)
        Let return_idx be type_args_total minus 1
        Let return_arg be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, return_idx
        Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with return_arg, config

    Otherwise If type_kind is equal to "binary":
        Set output to "<<>>"

    Otherwise If type_kind is equal to "union":
        Let ui be 0
        While ui is less than type_args_total:
            Let arg be proc list_get from ListPrim with type_args, ui
            Set output to output joined with emit_type_expr with arg, config

            If ui is less than type_args_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with " | "
            End If
            Set ui to ui plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return output
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION EMISSION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Erlang functions can have multiple clauses (pattern-matched
alternatives) separated by `;` and terminated by `.`. Each clause has
its own pattern list, optional guard sequence after `when`, and a
body of comma-separated expressions. Function bodies are indented
one level deeper than the clause headers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates func.clauses. For each clause: emits the function name and
opens `(`, then comma-separated patterns through emit_expression, then
`)`. If guards are non-empty appends ` when ` followed by emit_guards
output. Then ` ->` and newline. Increases indent, iterates body
expressions emitting each at the new indent with trailing `,` between
them (last body expression has no trailing comma). Decreases indent.
Between clauses emits `;` + newline; after the last clause emits `.`
to terminate the function.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_function" that takes func as ErlangFunction, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be ""
    Let func_name be func.name
    Let func_clauses be func.clauses

    Note: Emit all clauses. Clause count computed once into a local; While loop
    Note: (stage1 mis-evaluates a `For ... to <proc call> minus 1` bound).
    Let func_clauses_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with func_clauses
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than func_clauses_total:
        Let clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with func_clauses, i
        Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        Let clause_guards be clause.guards
        Let clause_body be clause.body

        Note: Function name and patterns
        Set output to output joined with func_name
        Set output to output joined with "("

        Let clause_patterns_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_patterns
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than clause_patterns_total:
            Let pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, j
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with pattern, config

            If j is less than clause_patterns_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ", "
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set output to output joined with ")"

        Note: Guards
        Let clause_guards_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_guards
        If clause_guards_total is greater than 0:
            Set output to output joined with " when "
            Set output to output joined with emit_guards with clause_guards, config
        End If

        Set output to output joined with " ->"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Note: Body
        Call increase_indent with config

        Let clause_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_body
        Let bj be 0
        While bj is less than clause_body_total:
            Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_body, bj
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

            If bj is less than clause_body_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ","
            End If

            Set output to output joined with "\n"
            Set bj to bj plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config

        Note: Clause separator or terminator
        If i is less than func_clauses_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ";"
            Set output to output joined with "\n"
        Otherwise:
            Set output to output joined with "."
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang guard syntax has two levels: a sequence of guards separated by
`;` (OR) where each guard is a sequence of tests separated by `,`
(AND). The doubly-nested list structure of the parameter mirrors this
exactly so emission is just two nested loops with the right separators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Outer loop iterates guard_seqs (alternatives, OR-separated). Inner
loop iterates each guard_seq (conjunction, AND-separated). Tests are
emitted through emit_expression. Inner separator is `, ` (comma-AND);
outer separator between alternatives is `; ` (semicolon-OR). Last
elements in each loop suppress the trailing separator.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_guards" that takes guard_seqs as List[List[ErlangExpression]], config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be ""

    Note: Guard sequences separated by semicolons
    Let guard_seqs_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with guard_seqs
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than guard_seqs_total:
        Let guard_seq be proc list_get from ListPrim with guard_seqs, i

        Note: Guard tests separated by commas
        Let guard_seq_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with guard_seq
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than guard_seq_total:
            Let guard_test be proc list_get from ListPrim with guard_seq, j
            Let guard_str be emit_expression with guard_test, config
            Set output to output joined with guard_str

            If j is less than guard_seq_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ", "
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        If i is less than guard_seqs_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with "; "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return output
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION EMISSION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The central expression dispatcher covering all Erlang expression kinds.
Twenty-two expression types route to either an inline branch (literals,
atoms, variables, integers, floats, characters, strings, macros) or a
specialised emit_X helper (lists, tuples, binaries, operators, calls,
funs, case/if/receive/try/begin, comprehensions, record create/access).
The fallback emits a `<<unsupported: name>>` marker rather than aborting
so unknown nodes surface as obvious text rather than crashing the emit
pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
String comparison on expr_type drives a long Otherwise If chain. Inline
branches: atom -> emit_atom on value (handles quoting), var -> raw
name, integer/float -> string-of-value, char -> `$` + value, string ->
quoted+escaped value, macro -> `?` + name. Helper branches delegate
to the specialised emit_X function which handles the full sub-shape
including indentation. Order matters only for the literal-then-complex
flow; otherwise tags are mutually exclusive.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_expression" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let output be ""
    Let expr_type be expr.expr_type
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data

    Note: Atom. Dict lookups are bound to locals before being passed as call
    Note: arguments or joined, because the stage1 codegen mis-evaluates an
    Note: `<dict> at key "..."` lookup used inline as a call argument.
    If expr_type is equal to "atom":
        Let atom_value be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "value"
        Set output to emit_atom with atom_value

    Note: Variable
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "var":
        Set output to proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "name"

    Note: Integer
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "integer":
        Let int_value be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "value"
        Set output to proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with int_value

    Note: Float - the parser stores the float's source lexeme verbatim as a
    Note: string to preserve its textual representation, so emit it directly.
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "float":
        Set output to proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "value"

    Note: Character
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "char":
        Let char_value be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "value"
        Set output to "$"
        Set output to output joined with char_value

    Note: String
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "string":
        Let string_value be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "value"
        Let escaped_string be escape_string with string_value
        Set output to "\""
        Set output to output joined with escaped_string
        Set output to output joined with "\""

    Note: List
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "list":
        Set output to emit_list with expr, config

    Note: Tuple
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "tuple":
        Set output to emit_tuple with expr, config

    Note: Binary
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "binary":
        Set output to emit_binary with expr, config

    Note: Binary operator
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "op":
        Set output to emit_binary_op with expr, config

    Note: Unary operator
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "unary_op":
        Set output to emit_unary_op with expr, config

    Note: Function call
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "call":
        Set output to emit_call with expr, config

    Note: Fun expression
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "fun":
        Set output to emit_fun with expr, config

    Note: Case expression
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "case":
        Set output to emit_case with expr, config

    Note: If expression
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "if":
        Set output to emit_if with expr, config

    Note: Receive expression
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "receive":
        Set output to emit_receive with expr, config

    Note: Try expression
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "try":
        Set output to emit_try with expr, config

    Note: Begin expression
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "begin":
        Set output to emit_begin with expr, config

    Note: List comprehension
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "list_comprehension":
        Set output to emit_list_comprehension with expr, config

    Note: Binary comprehension
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "binary_comprehension":
        Set output to emit_binary_comprehension with expr, config

    Note: Record creation
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "record_create":
        Set output to emit_record_create with expr, config

    Note: Record access
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "record_access":
        Set output to emit_record_access with expr, config

    Note: Macro
    Otherwise If expr_type is equal to "macro":
        Let macro_name be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "name"
        Set output to "?"
        Set output to output joined with macro_name

    Otherwise:
        Set output to "<<unsupported: "
        Set output to output joined with expr_type
        Set output to output joined with ">>"
    End If

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang atoms are bare lowercase identifiers; anything else (uppercase
start, special characters, spaces) needs single-quote wrapping like
'X' or '$bar'. Quoting decisions are encapsulated here so call sites
don't repeat the lexical test.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls needs_quoting; on true wraps the value in `'...'`. Returns the
bare value otherwise. No escaping of internal quotes inside the atom
string — assumes the parser already validated the atom contains no
unescaped `'` characters.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_atom" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if atom needs quoting
    Let must_quote be needs_quoting with value
    If must_quote:
        Return "'" joined with value joined with "'"
    End If

    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Determines whether an Erlang atom requires single-quote wrapping. An
unquoted atom must start with a lowercase letter and contain only
letters, digits, `_`, or `@`. Anything else — empty, uppercase start,
or any special character — must be quoted.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Length 0 returns true (empty atoms must be quoted as `''`). Compares
the first character against the uppercase A-Z range — returns true
if uppercase. Then iterates a list of 34 special characters (space,
punctuation, brackets, operators); if any of them appears anywhere
in the atom returns true. Otherwise returns false.
@End Implementation

Process called "needs_quoting" that takes atom as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Atom needs quoting if it starts with uppercase or contains special chars
    If length of atom is equal to 0:
        Return true
    End If

    Let first_char be substring of atom from 0 to 1

    Note: Check if starts with lowercase
    If first_char is greater than or equal to "A" and first_char is less than or equal to "Z":
        Return true
    End If

    Note:
    Check for special characters that require quoting. Membership is tested with
    string_index_of (>= 0 means the character occurs in the atom) rather than the
    `contains` keyword: on a String operand `contains` lowers to a list-membership
    call that treats the String handle as a RunaList and dereferences it as one,
    which faults. string_index_of is the String-typed search primitive.
    :End Note
    Let special_chars be a list containing " ", "-", "!", "@", "#", "$", "%", "^", "&", "*", "(", ")", "+", "=", "[", "]", "{", "}", "|", "\\", ":", ";", "\"", "'", "<", ">", ",", ".", "?", "/", "~", "`"

    For Each special_char in special_chars:
        Let occurrence be proc string_index_of from StringPrim with atom, special_char
        If occurrence is greater than or equal to 0:
            Return true
        End If
    End For

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
String literals in Erlang use C-style escapes for `"`, `\`, newline,
and tab. Other control characters survive raw — Erlang strings are
just integer lists so byte-level content is preserved, but the four
characters listed must be escaped to avoid breaking string literal
syntax in the generated source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the string character by character, comparing each against
the four escape-required chars. Matches emit the escaped two-byte
form (\", \\, \n, \t); other characters pass through unchanged.
Returns the assembled escaped string.
@End Implementation

Process called "escape_string" that takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Escape special characters in string
    Let result be ""

    For i from 0 to length of str minus 1:
        Let char be substring of str from i to i plus 1

        If char is equal to "\"":
            Set result to result joined with "\\\""
        Otherwise If char is equal to "\\":
            Set result to result joined with "\\\\"
        Otherwise If char is equal to "\n":
            Set result to result joined with "\\n"
        Otherwise If char is equal to "\t":
            Set result to result joined with "\\t"
        Otherwise:
            Set result to result joined with char
        End If
    End For

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang supports both proper lists `[a, b, c]` and improper lists with
explicit tails `[a, b | Tail]`. The tail field distinguishes the two —
when non-null it signals improper-list syntax. Improper lists are
common in pattern matching where the tail is a variable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Opens `[`, iterates elements emitting each with `, ` separator (no
trailing comma on last). If tail is non-zero, appends ` | ` followed
by the recursively-emitted tail expression. Closes with `]`. Empty
lists produce `[]` exactly.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_list" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    expr_data entries are read through the canonical dictionary `get` primitive:
    the stage1 codegen lowers an `at key` read of these dict-literal-stored
    handles to a load that returns 0, which would drop the list elements.
    :End Note
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let elements be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "elements"
    Let tail be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "tail"

    Let output be "["

    Let elements_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with elements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than elements_total:
        Let element be proc list_get from ListPrim with elements, i
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with element, config

        If i is less than elements_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Improper list with tail
    If tail is not equal to 0:
        Set output to output joined with " | "
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with tail, config
    End If

    Set output to output joined with "]"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang tuples use brace syntax `{a, b, c}` and are heterogeneously
typed. Empty tuple `{}` is allowed (the unit tuple, sometimes used
as a sentinel value).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Opens `{`, iterates elements with comma-space separators (no trailing
comma), closes `}`. Each element is recursively emit_expression. No
single-element special case needed — Erlang tuples don't have the
comma-disambiguation problem that exists in some other languages.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_tuple" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let elements be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "elements"

    Let output be "{"

    Let elements_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with elements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than elements_total:
        Let element be proc list_get from ListPrim with elements, i
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with element, config

        If i is less than elements_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set output to output joined with "}"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang binaries `<<a, b:8, c/integer-big>>` are a sequence of segments
where each segment has a value, optional size, and optional list of
type specifiers (integer/float/binary/big/little/native/signed/unsigned).
The slash-separated specifier list and colon-prefixed size encode all
the bit-level layout info.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Opens `<<`. Iterates segments. For each: emits the value through
emit_expression; if size is non-zero appends `:` + size expression;
if specifiers list is non-empty appends `/` followed by specifiers
joined with `-`. Comma-space between segments. Closes `>>`. Empty
binaries produce `<<>>` exactly.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_binary" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let segments be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "segments"

    Let output be "<<"

    Let segments_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with segments
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than segments_total:
        Let segment be proc list_get from ListPrim with segments, i
        Let segment_value be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "value"
        Let segment_value_str be emit_expression with segment_value, config
        Set output to output joined with segment_value_str

        Note: Size specifier
        Let segment_size be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "size"
        If segment_size is not equal to 0:
            Set output to output joined with ":"
            Let segment_size_str be emit_expression with segment_size, config
            Set output to output joined with segment_size_str
        End If

        Note: Type specifiers
        Let specifiers be proc get from DictPrim with segment, "specifiers"
        Let specifiers_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with specifiers
        If specifiers_total is greater than 0:
            Set output to output joined with "/"

            Let j be 0
            While j is less than specifiers_total:
                Let specifier be proc list_get from ListPrim with specifiers, j
                Set output to output joined with specifier

                If j is less than specifiers_total minus 1:
                    Set output to output joined with "-"
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        If i is less than segments_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set output to output joined with ">>"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Most Erlang binary operators (+, -, *, /, ++, --, andalso, etc.) are
emitted with single spaces around them. The exception is the remote-
module operator `:` (mod:func), which must NOT have surrounding spaces.
Distinguishing the colon case keeps generated code lexically valid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads operator string and recursively emits left and right operands.
If operator is `:`, returns `left:right` with no spaces (module:func
call syntax). Otherwise returns `left OP right` with spaces around
the operator. No precedence-based parenthesization — the parser is
expected to have produced sufficiently-parenthesized expressions, or
the printer will produce ambiguous output that re-parses to a
different AST.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_binary_op" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let operator be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "operator"
    Let left_node be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "left"
    Let right_node be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "right"
    Let left be emit_expression with left_node, config
    Let right be emit_expression with right_node, config

    Note: Handle special operators
    If operator is equal to ":":
        Note: Remote call - no spaces
        Return left joined with ":" joined with right
    End If

    Note: Standard binary operators with spaces
    Return left joined with " " joined with operator joined with " " joined with right
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang unary operators (-, +, not, bnot) prefix the operand directly
without a space. This matches Erlang lexical rules where, e.g.,
`-X` is the unary-minus expression while `- X` would also parse but
the canonical form has no space.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads operator and operand, recursively emits operand, returns
concatenation `operator + operand`. Word operators like `not` will
produce `notX` which is wrong — caller is expected to ensure word
operators have trailing space in the operator string, or the parser
canonicalizes word operators into prefix-call form before this point.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_unary_op" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let operator be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "operator"
    Let operand_node be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "operand"
    Let operand be emit_expression with operand_node, config

    Return operator joined with operand
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang function calls have the form `Function(Arg1, Arg2, ...)` where
Function can be a local atom, an mfa expression (mod:func), or a
higher-order value (variable bound to a fun). Recursive emit_expression
on the function part handles all three cases uniformly — module:func
will have been emitted as a binary-op with `:` operator producing
correct mfa syntax.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Recursively emits the function expression, then `(`, then comma-space
separated arguments through emit_expression. Last argument has no
trailing comma. Closes `)`. Zero-arg calls produce `Function()` which
is the correct Erlang form.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_call" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let function_node be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "function"
    Let function be emit_expression with function_node, config
    Let arguments be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "arguments"

    Let output be function
    Set output to output joined with "("

    Let arguments_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with arguments
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arguments_total:
        Let argument be proc list_get from ListPrim with arguments, i
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with argument, config

        If i is less than arguments_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set output to output joined with ")"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's `fun` expression covers three distinct forms with different
syntax: `fun mod:func/Arity` (remote reference), `fun func/Arity`
(local reference), and `fun ... end` (anonymous function with one or
more pattern-matched clauses). Each requires different emission so
the fun_type field selects the path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switches on the `type` key. "remote_ref" returns `fun Mod:Func/Arity`.
"local_ref" returns `fun Func/Arity`. "anonymous" iterates the
clauses list emitting each clause's `(patterns) when Guards -> Body`
form with `;` between clauses, wrapped in `fun ... end`. The fallback
returns `fun() -> ok end` for malformed fun expressions — a valid
sentinel rather than an error string so downstream consumers don't
break on unrecognised input.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_fun" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let fun_type be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "type"

    Note: func_name and arity are written from both the remote_ref and local_ref
    Note: branches, so they are declared once at the top to give every branch a
    Note: live slot (the stage1 codegen leaves cross-branch-only Set targets null).
    Let func_name be ""
    Let arity be 0

    Note: Remote function reference
    If fun_type is equal to "remote_ref":
        Let module_name be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "module"
        Set func_name to proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "function"
        Set arity to proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "arity"
        Let arity_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with arity

        Return "fun " joined with module_name joined with ":" joined with func_name joined with "/" joined with arity_str

    Note: Local function reference
    Otherwise If fun_type is equal to "local_ref":
        Set func_name to proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "function"
        Set arity to proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "arity"
        Let local_arity_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrim with arity

        Return "fun " joined with func_name joined with "/" joined with local_arity_str
    End If

    Note: Anonymous function
    If fun_type is equal to "anonymous":
        Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "clauses"

        Let output be "fun"

        Let clauses_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than clauses_total:
            Let clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, i
            Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
            Let clause_guards be clause.guards
            Let clause_body be clause.body

            Set output to output joined with " ("

            Let clause_patterns_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_patterns
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than clause_patterns_total:
                Let pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, j
                Set output to output joined with emit_expression with pattern, config

                If j is less than clause_patterns_total minus 1:
                    Set output to output joined with ", "
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While

            Set output to output joined with ")"

            Note: Guards
            Let clause_guards_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_guards
            If clause_guards_total is greater than 0:
                Set output to output joined with " when "
                Set output to output joined with emit_guards with clause_guards, config
            End If

            Set output to output joined with " -> "

            Note: Body
            Let clause_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_body
            Let bj be 0
            While bj is less than clause_body_total:
                Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_body, bj
                Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

                If bj is less than clause_body_total minus 1:
                    Set output to output joined with ", "
                End If
                Set bj to bj plus 1
            End While

            If i is less than clauses_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with "; "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set output to output joined with " end"

        Return output
    End If

    Return "fun() -> ok end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang case expressions have the form `case Expr of Pattern [when
Guards] -> Body; ... end`. Bodies are indented relative to the case
keyword, the `end` aligns with `case`. Multi-clause cases use `;` as
clause separator; the last clause has no separator before `end`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `case Scrutinee of` followed by newline, increases indent.
Iterates clauses. Each clause emits at current indent: first pattern
(patterns[0]; case clauses are single-pattern by Erlang grammar),
optional ` when Guards`, ` ->`, newline. Body lines emit at a further-
increased indent with `,` between body expressions. After each clause
except the last, emits `;` then newline. After all clauses, decreases
indent twice (clause body, then outer) and emits the indented `end`
that aligns with the original case statement.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_case" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let scrutinee_node be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "scrutinee"
    Let scrutinee be emit_expression with scrutinee_node, config
    Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "clauses"

    Let output be "case "
    Set output to output joined with scrutinee
    Set output to output joined with " of"
    Set output to output joined with "\n"

    Call increase_indent with config

    Let clauses_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than clauses_total:
        Let clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, i
        Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        Let clause_guards be clause.guards
        Let clause_body be clause.body

        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Let first_pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, 0
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with first_pattern, config

        Note: Guards
        Let clause_guards_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_guards
        If clause_guards_total is greater than 0:
            Set output to output joined with " when "
            Set output to output joined with emit_guards with clause_guards, config
        End If

        Set output to output joined with " ->"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Call increase_indent with config

        Let clause_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_body
        Let bj be 0
        While bj is less than clause_body_total:
            Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_body, bj
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

            If bj is less than clause_body_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ","
            End If

            Set output to output joined with "\n"
            Set bj to bj plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config

        If i is less than clauses_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with ";"
            Set output to output joined with "\n"
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Call decrease_indent with config

    Set output to output joined with indent with config
    Set output to output joined with "end"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang `if Guards -> Body; ... end` has no scrutinee and no patterns;
only guard sequences. Each clause's guards are emitted through
emit_guards; semantics are first-matching wins. The structure is
otherwise identical to case emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `if` + newline, increases indent. Iterates clauses, each emitted
at current indent. Clause emits guards (no patterns), ` ->`, newline,
body at further-increased indent with `,` between body expressions.
After each clause except the last, emits `;` + newline. After loop
decreases indent and emits indented `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_if" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "clauses"

    Let output be "if"
    Set output to output joined with "\n"

    Call increase_indent with config

    Let clauses_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than clauses_total:
        Let clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, i
        Let clause_guards be clause.guards
        Let clause_body be clause.body

        Set output to output joined with indent with config

        Note: Guards (if uses only guards, no patterns)
        Let clause_guards_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_guards
        If clause_guards_total is greater than 0:
            Set output to output joined with emit_guards with clause_guards, config
        End If

        Set output to output joined with " ->"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Call increase_indent with config

        Let clause_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_body
        Let bj be 0
        While bj is less than clause_body_total:
            Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_body, bj
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

            If bj is less than clause_body_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ","
            End If

            Set output to output joined with "\n"
            Set bj to bj plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config

        If i is less than clauses_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with ";"
            Set output to output joined with "\n"
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Call decrease_indent with config

    Set output to output joined with indent with config
    Set output to output joined with "end"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang `receive` blocks `receive Patterns -> Body; ... after Timeout
-> Body end` are the message-passing primitive. The optional `after`
clause runs if no message arrives in Timeout milliseconds. The
separator between the last receive clause and the after clause is `;`,
matching the inter-clause separator — the absence-of-after case omits
that separator on the last clause.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `receive` + newline, increases indent. Iterates message-match
clauses similar to case but the separator decision considers both
"more clauses follow" and "after clause is present": `;` is emitted
if either is true. Body emission inside each clause uses an extra
indent level. After clauses iterate, optionally emits `after Timeout
-> Body` block also at the inner indent. Then decreases indent and
emits indented `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_receive" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let clauses be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "clauses"
    Let after_timeout be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "after_timeout"
    Let after_body be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "after_body"

    Let output be "receive"
    Set output to output joined with "\n"

    Call increase_indent with config

    Note: Receive clauses
    Let clauses_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clauses
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than clauses_total:
        Let clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with clauses, i
        Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
        Let clause_guards be clause.guards
        Let clause_body be clause.body

        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Let first_pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, 0
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with first_pattern, config

        Let clause_guards_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_guards
        If clause_guards_total is greater than 0:
            Set output to output joined with " when "
            Set output to output joined with emit_guards with clause_guards, config
        End If

        Set output to output joined with " ->"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Call increase_indent with config

        Let clause_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_body
        Let bj be 0
        While bj is less than clause_body_total:
            Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_body, bj
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

            If bj is less than clause_body_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ","
            End If

            Set output to output joined with "\n"
            Set bj to bj plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config

        Note: Separator before next clause or before the after-block. The
        Note: "more clauses follow" test is bound to a local first so the
        Note: compound condition tests two simple locals (stage1 mis-evaluates
        Note: a `length of`-derived term inside a compound condition).
        Let more_clauses_follow be i is less than clauses_total minus 1
        If more_clauses_follow is true or after_timeout is not equal to 0:
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with ";"
            Set output to output joined with "\n"
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: After clause
    If after_timeout is not equal to 0:
        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Set output to output joined with "after "
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with after_timeout, config
        Set output to output joined with " ->"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Call increase_indent with config

        Let after_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with after_body
        Let abj be 0
        While abj is less than after_body_total:
            Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with after_body, abj
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

            If abj is less than after_body_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ","
            End If

            Set output to output joined with "\n"
            Set abj to abj plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config
    End If

    Call decrease_indent with config

    Set output to output joined with indent with config
    Set output to output joined with "end"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang `try Body [of Patterns -> ...] [catch ExceptionClass:Pattern
[when Guards] -> ...] [after Body] end` is the exception-handling
construct. All four sections (body / of / catch / after) are optional
except body. Catch clauses have a unique two-part pattern (`Class:Pat`)
distinguishing them from case-style single-pattern clauses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `try` + newline, increases indent. Body section: each expression
emitted at current indent with `,` between, newline at end. Decreases
indent. Then conditional `of` section with case-style clause emission
if of_clauses non-empty. Then conditional `catch` section where each
catch clause emits optional `Class:` (skipping when exception_class
is null), then the exception pattern, optional ` when Guards`, then
` ->` + body. After clause emits its body indented under `after`.
Finally emits indented `end`. All nested sections maintain proper
indent depth through paired increase/decrease calls.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_try" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let try_body be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "try_body"
    Let of_clauses be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "of_clauses"
    Let catch_clauses be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "catch_clauses"
    Let after_body be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "after_body"

    Let output be "try"
    Set output to output joined with "\n"

    Call increase_indent with config

    Note: Try body
    Let try_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with try_body
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than try_body_total:
        Let try_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with try_body, i
        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with try_expr, config

        If i is less than try_body_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ","
        End If

        Set output to output joined with "\n"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Call decrease_indent with config

    Note: Of clauses
    Let of_clauses_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with of_clauses
    If of_clauses_total is greater than 0:
        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Set output to output joined with "of"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Call increase_indent with config

        Let oi be 0
        While oi is less than of_clauses_total:
            Let clause be proc list_get from ListPrim with of_clauses, oi
            Let clause_patterns be clause.patterns
            Let clause_guards be clause.guards
            Let clause_body be clause.body

            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Let first_pattern be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_patterns, 0
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with first_pattern, config

            Let clause_guards_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_guards
            If clause_guards_total is greater than 0:
                Set output to output joined with " when "
                Set output to output joined with emit_guards with clause_guards, config
            End If

            Set output to output joined with " ->"
            Set output to output joined with "\n"

            Call increase_indent with config

            Let clause_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with clause_body
            Let obj be 0
            While obj is less than clause_body_total:
                Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with clause_body, obj
                Set output to output joined with indent with config
                Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

                If obj is less than clause_body_total minus 1:
                    Set output to output joined with ","
                End If

                Set output to output joined with "\n"
                Set obj to obj plus 1
            End While

            Call decrease_indent with config

            If oi is less than of_clauses_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with indent with config
                Set output to output joined with ";"
                Set output to output joined with "\n"
            End If
            Set oi to oi plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config
    End If

    Note: Catch clauses
    Let catch_clauses_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with catch_clauses
    If catch_clauses_total is greater than 0:
        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Set output to output joined with "catch"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Call increase_indent with config

        Let ci be 0
        While ci is less than catch_clauses_total:
            Let catch_data be proc list_get from ListPrim with catch_clauses, ci

            Set output to output joined with indent with config

            Let exception_class be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "exception_class"
            If exception_class is not equal to 0:
                Let exception_class_str be emit_expression with exception_class, config
                Set output to output joined with exception_class_str
                Set output to output joined with ":"
            End If

            Let exception_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "exception_pattern"
            Let exception_pattern_str be emit_expression with exception_pattern, config
            Set output to output joined with exception_pattern_str

            Let guard_exprs be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "guards"
            Let guard_exprs_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with guard_exprs
            If guard_exprs_total is greater than 0:
                Set output to output joined with " when "
                Let gj be 0
                While gj is less than guard_exprs_total:
                    Let guard_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with guard_exprs, gj
                    Let guard_expr_str be emit_expression with guard_expr, config
                    Set output to output joined with guard_expr_str
                    If gj is less than guard_exprs_total minus 1:
                        Set output to output joined with ", "
                    End If
                    Set gj to gj plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Set output to output joined with " ->"
            Set output to output joined with "\n"

            Call increase_indent with config

            Let body be proc get from DictPrim with catch_data, "body"
            Let body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with body
            Let cbj be 0
            While cbj is less than body_total:
                Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with body, cbj
                Let body_expr_str be emit_expression with body_expr, config
                Set output to output joined with indent with config
                Set output to output joined with body_expr_str

                If cbj is less than body_total minus 1:
                    Set output to output joined with ","
                End If

                Set output to output joined with "\n"
                Set cbj to cbj plus 1
            End While

            Call decrease_indent with config

            If ci is less than catch_clauses_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with indent with config
                Set output to output joined with ";"
                Set output to output joined with "\n"
            End If
            Set ci to ci plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config
    End If

    Note: After clause
    Let after_body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with after_body
    If after_body_total is greater than 0:
        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Set output to output joined with "after"
        Set output to output joined with "\n"

        Call increase_indent with config

        Let ai be 0
        While ai is less than after_body_total:
            Let after_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with after_body, ai
            Set output to output joined with indent with config
            Set output to output joined with emit_expression with after_expr, config

            If ai is less than after_body_total minus 1:
                Set output to output joined with ","
            End If

            Set output to output joined with "\n"
            Set ai to ai plus 1
        End While

        Call decrease_indent with config
    End If

    Set output to output joined with indent with config
    Set output to output joined with "end"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's `begin ... end` block sequences expressions and returns the
last one's value — used wherever a single expression slot needs to
contain multiple statements (e.g., a case-clause body cannot directly
hold a comma list in some grammars).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `begin` + newline. Increases indent. Iterates body expressions
emitting each at the current indent with `,` between (no trailing
comma on last). Decreases indent and emits indented `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_begin" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let body be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "body"

    Let output be "begin"
    Set output to output joined with "\n"

    Call increase_indent with config

    Let body_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with body
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than body_total:
        Let body_expr be proc list_get from ListPrim with body, i
        Set output to output joined with indent with config
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with body_expr, config

        If i is less than body_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ","
        End If

        Set output to output joined with "\n"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Call decrease_indent with config

    Set output to output joined with indent with config
    Set output to output joined with "end"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang list comprehensions `[Template || Pat <- List, Filter, ...]`
have a template expression and a list of qualifiers. Qualifiers are
either generators (pattern <- source list) or filters (boolean
expressions). Multiple qualifiers are evaluated left to right.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Opens `[`, emits the template expression, then ` || `. Iterates
qualifiers. For each: "generator" emits `Pat <- List` (both
recursively emit_expression); "filter" emits just the boolean
expression. Comma-space between qualifiers. Closes `]`. The qualifier
type field is required — unknown types produce empty output but the
list is still validly bracketed.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_list_comprehension" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let template_node be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "template"
    Let template be emit_expression with template_node, config
    Let qualifiers be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "qualifiers"

    Let output be "["
    Set output to output joined with template
    Set output to output joined with " || "

    Let qualifiers_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with qualifiers
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than qualifiers_total:
        Let qualifier be proc list_get from ListPrim with qualifiers, i
        Let qual_type be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "type"
        Note:
        The qualifier tag is compared with string_equals (content) rather than
        `is equal to`, which tests String handle identity under the stage1
        codegen and would skip the generator arm, dropping `Pat <- List`.
        :End Note
        Let lcp_is_gen be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "generator"
        Let lcp_is_filter be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "filter"

        If lcp_is_gen is equal to 1:
            Let gen_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "pattern"
            Let gen_pattern_str be emit_expression with gen_pattern, config
            Set output to output joined with gen_pattern_str
            Set output to output joined with " <- "
            Let gen_list be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "list"
            Let gen_list_str be emit_expression with gen_list, config
            Set output to output joined with gen_list_str

        Otherwise If lcp_is_filter is equal to 1:
            Let filter_expr be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "expression"
            Let filter_expr_str be emit_expression with filter_expr, config
            Set output to output joined with filter_expr_str
        End If

        If i is less than qualifiers_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set output to output joined with "]"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang binary comprehensions `<<Template || Qualifiers>>` produce
binaries instead of lists. They support an additional qualifier kind
"binary_generator" using `<=` arrow (versus `<-` for list generators).
The template is itself a binary segment so it also has size and
specifier components.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Opens `<<`, emits template's value via emit_expression. If template
has a size (size != 0), emits `:size`. Then ` || ` and qualifier loop.
Three qualifier kinds: "generator" emits `Pat <- Source`,
"binary_generator" emits `Pat <= Source`, "filter" emits expression.
Comma-space between qualifiers. Closes `>>`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_binary_comprehension" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let template be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "template"
    Let qualifiers be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "qualifiers"

    Let output be "<<"

    Note: Emit template (binary segment)
    Let template_value be proc get from DictPrim with template, "value"
    Let template_value_str be emit_expression with template_value, config
    Set output to output joined with template_value_str

    Let template_size be proc get from DictPrim with template, "size"
    If template_size is not equal to 0:
        Set output to output joined with ":"
        Let template_size_str be emit_expression with template_size, config
        Set output to output joined with template_size_str
    End If

    Set output to output joined with " || "

    Let qualifiers_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with qualifiers
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than qualifiers_total:
        Let qualifier be proc list_get from ListPrim with qualifiers, i
        Let qual_type be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "type"
        Note:
        Tags compared with string_equals (content) rather than `is equal to`
        (handle identity under stage1), so each qualifier arm is selected.
        :End Note
        Let bcp_is_gen be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "generator"
        Let bcp_is_bgen be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "binary_generator"
        Let bcp_is_filter be proc string_equals from StringCore with qual_type, "filter"

        If bcp_is_gen is equal to 1:
            Let gen_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "pattern"
            Let gen_pattern_str be emit_expression with gen_pattern, config
            Set output to output joined with gen_pattern_str
            Set output to output joined with " <- "
            Let gen_source be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "source"
            Let gen_source_str be emit_expression with gen_source, config
            Set output to output joined with gen_source_str

        Otherwise If bcp_is_bgen is equal to 1:
            Let bgen_pattern be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "pattern"
            Let bgen_pattern_str be emit_expression with bgen_pattern, config
            Set output to output joined with bgen_pattern_str
            Set output to output joined with " <= "
            Let bgen_source be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "source"
            Let bgen_source_str be emit_expression with bgen_source, config
            Set output to output joined with bgen_source_str

        Otherwise If bcp_is_filter is equal to 1:
            Let bc_filter_expr be proc get from DictPrim with qualifier, "expression"
            Let bc_filter_expr_str be emit_expression with bc_filter_expr, config
            Set output to output joined with bc_filter_expr_str
        End If

        If i is less than qualifiers_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set output to output joined with ">>"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang record creation `#Name{field = Value, ...}` or record update
`Base#Name{field = Value, ...}`. The `base` field distinguishes the
two — when non-null the syntax includes `BaseExpr |` after the opening
brace. Fields not mentioned in an update inherit values from base;
fields not mentioned in a create get the default from the record
declaration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `#Name{`. If base is non-zero, emits the base expression followed
by ` | `. Then iterates fields emitting `name = Value` for each with
`, ` between entries. Closes `}`. Record field names are atoms but
emitted bare here since record field syntax doesn't quote them.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_record_create" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let name be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "name"
    Let fields be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "fields"
    Let base be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "base"

    Let output be "#"
    Set output to output joined with name
    Set output to output joined with "{"

    Note: Base record for update
    If base is not equal to 0:
        Set output to output joined with emit_expression with base, config
        Set output to output joined with " | "
    End If

    Let fields_total be proc list_length from ListPrim with fields
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than fields_total:
        Let field be proc list_get from ListPrim with fields, i
        Let field_name be proc get from DictPrim with field, "name"
        Set output to output joined with field_name
        Set output to output joined with " = "
        Let field_value be proc get from DictPrim with field, "value"
        Let field_value_str be emit_expression with field_value, config
        Set output to output joined with field_value_str

        If i is less than fields_total minus 1:
            Set output to output joined with ", "
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set output to output joined with "}"

    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang record field access syntax `Record#field` reads a single field
value. The `#` immediately follows the record expression with no
spaces; the field name is a bare atom.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Recursively emits the record expression, concatenates `#`, then the
field name. Single-line output, no indentation involved.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_record_access" that takes expr as ErlangExpression, config as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr_data be expr.expr_data
    Let record_node be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "record"
    Let record be emit_expression with record_node, config
    Let field be proc get from DictPrim with expr_data, "field"

    Return record joined with "#" joined with field
End Process

@Reasoning:
Used by attribute emission for the generic-value fallback when the
attribute type isn't `module`/`export`/`import`. Erlang attribute
values can be arbitrary terms (atoms, integers, lists, nested terms)
so this helper covers the three common term shapes with a default
catchall.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-way dispatch on Runa runtime type predicates: String -> emit
literally, Integer -> string-of-int, List -> recursive emission of
each element wrapped in `[...]` with `, ` separators. Falls through
to `"ok"` for any other type — a defensive sentinel rather than an
error string so attribute output remains lexically valid Erlang even
if a structurally-invalid term sneaks through.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_term" that takes term as Any returns Integer:
    Note:
    Erlang terms in attribute position are materialised by the parser's
    parse_term into their canonical Erlang text (atoms/integers/strings as their
    lexeme; lists as "[...]"; tuples as "{...}"), so a term reaches this emitter
    already as a ready-to-write String. Emitting it is therefore a direct return
    of that text - no runtime type dispatch is required (and the code generator
    cannot perform one). A null term degrades to the lexically-valid atom "ok"
    so attribute output stays well-formed.
    :End Note
    If term is equal to 0:
        Return "ok"
    End If
    Return term
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EMISSION ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point used by the rest of the compiler when it needs to
turn an ErlangModule AST back into source text. Creates a default
config so callers don't have to know about indentation settings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_emitter_config to get default formatting, then delegates
to emit_module which does the actual work. No config disposal needed
because ErlangEmitterConfig is a plain value type with no owned heap
resources.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_erlang_module" that takes module as ErlangModule returns Integer:
    Let config be create_emitter_config
    Return emit_module with module, config
End Process
